title: Railroad - Widgets and Attributes

! Widgets and Attributes — Railroad Diagrams

This tiddler presents the same widget and attribute syntax as [[EBNF - Widgets and Attributes]], but using railroad diagrams for visual clarity. Follow the tracks left-to-right to see valid syntax paths.

!! HTML Elements and Widgets

The same parser rule ([[html.js|https://github.com/TiddlyWiki/TiddlyWiki5/blob/master/core/modules/parsers/wikiparser/rules/html.js]]) handles both plain HTML elements and TiddlyWiki widgets. Widgets use a `$` prefix on their tag name. If the opening tag is followed by a blank line, content is parsed in block mode; otherwise inline mode.

!!! Tag Name

A tag is either a `$`-prefixed widget name or a plain HTML tag name.

<$railroad text=""" ("$" <"widget-name"> | <"html-tag-name">) """/>

!!! Element Structure

An element is an opening tag with optional attributes, then either self-closing or wrapping content.

<$railroad text=""" "<" <"tag-name"> [{<"attribute">}] ("/>" | ">" <"content"> "</" <"tag-name"> ">") """/>

!! The Attribute System

This is the most complex part of wikitext syntax. An attribute is a name optionally followed by `=` and a value. The parser in [[parseutils.js|https://github.com/TiddlyWiki/TiddlyWiki5/blob/master/core/modules/parsers/parseutils.js]] tries each value form in order, taking the first match.

!!! Attribute

An attribute name alone (no `=`) means boolean `"true"`. With `=`, a value follows.

<$railroad text=""" <"attr-name"> ["=" <"attr-value">] """/>

!!! Attribute Value (all 7 forms)

The value after `=` can take any of these forms. They are tried in the order shown (top to bottom).

<$railroad text="""(
  :<"string-literal"> / "quoted string" /
| "{{{" <"filter-expr"> "}}}" / "filtered" /
| "{{" <"text-reference"> "}}" / "indirect" /
| "<<" <"macro-call"> ">>" / "macro or variable" /
| "((" <"var-name"> "))" / "MVV" /
| <"substituted-value"> / "backtick-quoted" /
| <"unquoted-value"> / "bare value" /
)"""/>

!!! String Literal

Four quoting styles. Triple-double-quote allows embedded double quotes and newlines.

<$railroad text=`(
  :'"""' <"any-text"> '"""' / "triple-double-quote" /
| '"' <"text"> '"' / "double-quoted" /
| "'" <"text"> "'" / "single-quoted" /
| "[[" <"text"> "]]" / "double-bracket" /
)`/>

!! Substituted Attributes

Inside backtick-quoted attribute values, `$(varname)$` placeholders provide text substitution at runtime. Multiple placeholders can appear in a single value.

!!! Substituted Text

The content between backticks is a mix of plain text and variable placeholders.

<$railroad text=""" [{(<"plain-text"> | "$(" <"var-name"> ")$")}] """/>

!!! Single-line vs Multi-line

Single backticks for one line, triple backticks for multiline values that can contain single backticks.

<$railroad text="""(
  :<"backtick"> <"substituted-text"> <"backtick"> / "single-line" /
| <"triple-backtick"> <"substituted-text"> <"triple-backtick"> / "multiline" /
)"""/>

!! Parse Order

The `parseAttribute()` function tries value forms in this specific order after seeing `=`:

# String literal (`"..."`, `'...'`, `[[...]]`, `"""..."""`) — checked first via `parseStringLiteral()`
# Filtered value (`{{{...}}}`)
# Indirect value (`{{...}}`)
# Macro invocation (`<<...>>`)
# MVV reference (`((...))`) 
# Substituted value (backtick or triple-backtick delimited)
# Unquoted value (any run of non-delimiter characters)
# Fallback: value is `"true"`

This ordering matters. For example, `{{{filter}}}` is checked before `{{textref}}`, so there is no ambiguity. Similarly, `<<macro>>` is checked before unquoted values, so angle brackets are never part of a bare value.

